个儿子。"},"hr":{"about 1213–":"oko 1213.–preminuo","1217–Female":"1217–preminula","1230–1280":"1230.–1280","1213–Male":"1213–preminuo","1217":"1217","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1213":"1213","about 1213":"oko 1213.","1230":"1230.","1280":"1280","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, England","England":"England"},"cs":{"about 1213–":"okolo 1213–Zesnulý","1217–Female":"1217–Zesnulá","1230–1280":"1230–1280","1213–Male":"1213–Zesnulý","1217":"1217","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1213":"1213","about 1213":"okolo 1213","1230":"1230","1280":"1280","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, Anglie","England":"Anglie"},"da":{"about 1213–":"omkring 1213–Afdød","1217–Female":"1217–Afdød","1230–1280":"1230–1280","1213–Male":"1213–Afdød","1217":"1217","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1213":"1213","about 1213":"omkring 1213","1230":"1230","1280":"1280","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, England","England":"England"},"nl":{"about 1213–":"circa 1213–Overleden","1217–Female":"1217–Overleden","1230–1280":"1230–1280","1213–Male":"1213–Overleden","1217":"1217","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1213":"1213","about 1213":"circa 1213","1230":"1230","1280":"1280","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, England","England":"England"},"en":{"about 1213–":"about 1213–Deceased","1217–Female":"1217–Deceased","1230–1280":"1230–1280","1213–Male":"1213–Deceased","1217":"1217","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1213":"1213","about 1213":"about 1213","1230":"1230","1280":"1280","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Chaucer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: occupational name from Old French  <i>chaucier</i> ‘maker of  <i>chausses</i>’, an agent derivative of Old French  <i>chauces</i> ‘breeches, pantaloons, hose’. In 1484 these were ‘chauces of yron or legge harneys’ (   OED  ). Middle English  <i>chauce</i> was a general term for anything worn on the feet: boots, shoes, hose, or leggings. As Baldwin le Chaucer (1307   London Letter Books   B) was of  <i>Cordwanerstrete</i>, the early  <i>chaucer</i> was probably a worker in leather, a maker of leather breeches, boots, etc."],"variants":[{"name":"London Letter Books","meanings":["1  English: nickname, variant of the Norman name   Petchey   (Old French  <i>peché</i>, Middle English  <i>peche</i> ‘sin’). Medieval spellings with final  <i>-e</i> can represent either  <i>peché</i> or  <i>peche</i>, so some of the earliest of the following bearers may belong with  <i>Petchey</i> rather than  <i>Petch</i>, but the two forms of the name were in any case interchangeable. Compare John Peche, tailor, 1320, identical with J. Pecchee, 1328 in   London Letter Books   E; John Peche, 1558, Moses Pechey, 1584 in   IGI   (West Hanningfield, Essex).","2  English: variant of   Spetch   with loss of initial  <i>S-</i> (unless  <i>Spetch</i> itself is a variant of  <i>Petch</i> with a prosthetic  <i>S-</i>). The two names were certainly interchangeable.   Redmonds, Dictionary of Yorks Surnames   notes Michael Petch or Spetch (1609–13) and Lancelot or Lance Petch or Spetch (1625–7) in the Leeds parish registers; and Benjamin Petch otherwise Spetch, 1764 in   WR Yorks Quarter Sessions   (Azerley, WR Yorks). Compare also Thome Peche, 1586, Margret Spetche, 1594 in   IGI   (Londonthorpe, Lincs); Thomas Spech, 1589, Richd. Petch, 1726 in   IGI   (Whitgift, WR Yorks)."]},{"name":"Causer","meanings":["English (West Midlands): probably a variant of <b>Chauser</b>, an occupational name for a maker of leggings or other apparel for the legs or feet, from an agent derivative probably of a northern variant of Old French <i>cauc(i)er</i>, <i>chaucier</i> ‘maker of hose, shoemaker’, although <i>Cauc(i)er</i>, the Norman and Picard form of the name, has not yet been noted in English medieval records. Alternatively, perhaps a variant of <b>Cosier</b>, an occupational name from Middle English <i>cosere</i> ‘horse dealer’."]},{"name":"OED","meanings":["1  English: possibly a suffixed form of Middle English  <i>sere</i> ‘dry, withered’, seen also for example in Godefridus Seredust, 1199 in   Curia Regis Rolls  . Such extended adjectives are sometimes found in Early Modern English, as in  <i>stouty</i> and the surviving  <i>lanky</i>. ‘… certain monosyllabic adjs. were extended by means of this suffix, app[arently] with the design of giving them a more adjectival appearance … The majority of such words arose in the 16th and 17th cent.” (   OED  ).","2  Irish: from  <b>Ó Saoraidhe</b>,  see  Seery  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":2,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705188,"age":11,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705189,"age":46,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Chaucer was born about 1213, in England. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Chaucer."},"et":{"about 1213–":"umbes 1213–Surnud","1217–Female":"1217–Surnud","1230–1280":"1230–1280","1213–Male":"1213–Surnud","1217":"1217","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1213":"1213","about 1213":"umbes 1213","1230":"1230","1280":"1280","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"about 1213–":"noin 1213–Kuollut","1217–Female":"1217–Kuollut","1230–1280":"1230–1280","1213–Male":"1213–Kuollut","1217":"1217","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1213":"1213","about 1213":"noin 1213","1230":"1230","1280":"1280","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, England","England":"England"},"fr":{"about 1213–":"environ 1213–Décédé","1217–Female":"1217–Décédée","1230–1280":"1230–1280","1213–Male":"1213–Décédé","1217":"1217","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1213":"1213","about 1213":"environ 1213","1230":"1230","1280":"1280","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Chaucer est né environ 1213, à Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Mrs. Chaucer."},"de":{"about 1213–":"um 1213–Verstorben","1217–Female":"1217–Verstorben","1230–1280":"1230–1280","1213–Male":"1213–Verstorben","1217":"1217","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1213":"1213","about 1213":"um 1213","1230":"1230","1280":"1280","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, England","England":"England","lifeSummary":"Chaucer wurde um 1213 in England geboren. Er hatte mit Mrs. Chaucer mindestens 1 Sohn."},"ht":{"about 1213–":"about 1213–Desede","1217–Female":"1217–Desede","1230–1280":"1230–1280","1213–Male":"1213–Desede","1217":"1217","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1213":"1213","about 1213":"about 1213","1230":"1230","1280":"1280","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, England","England":"England"},"hu":{"about 1213–":"1213 körül–elhunyt","1217–Female":"1217–elhunyt","1230–1280":"1230–1280","1213–Male":"1213–elhunyt","1217":"1217","1259":"1259","1215":"1215"